{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17617802","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17617802"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:17:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:17:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16489"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16489","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16489"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.76,0.12,0.05,0.05,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9180"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65916"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9180","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9180"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16489"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51362"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5078"},{"type":"tags","id":"8452"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21787"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22019"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65916","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65916"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EMontelukast is commonly prescribed as an add-on medication for patients with persistent asthma.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of montelukast?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Blocks leukotriene receptors","Inhibits mast cell degranulation","Stimulates beta-2 adrenergic receptors","Blocks histamine receptors","Inhibits phosphodiesterase enzyme"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMontelukast works by \u003Cstrong\u003Eblocking leukotriene receptors\u003C/strong\u003E, specifically the cysteinyl leukotriene type 1 receptor. This prevents the binding of leukotrienes, which are important mediators of airway inflammation and bronchoconstriction in asthma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options represent different mechanisms of action in asthma treatment:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits mast cell degranulation\u003C/strong\u003E: while this would reduce inflammatory mediator release, montelukast does not directly affect mast cell function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulates beta-2 adrenergic receptors\u003C/strong\u003E: this mechanism causes bronchodilation through smooth muscle relaxation, but is not how montelukast works.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks histamine receptors\u003C/strong\u003E: tlthough histamine is involved in allergic responses, montelukast specifically targets leukotriene pathways.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits phosphodiesterase enzyme\u003C/strong\u003E: this would increase cyclic AMP levels leading to bronchodilation, but is not montelukast\u0027s mechanism of action.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBy blocking leukotriene receptors, montelukast reduces airway inflammation, mucus secretion, and bronchial hyperresponsiveness. It is particularly useful in exercise-induced asthma and as add-on therapy in persistent asthma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Montelukast is a selective leukotriene receptor antagonist that blocks the binding of cysteinyl leukotrienes to their receptors.","Leukotrienes are important mediators of bronchial inflammation and constriction in asthma.","Montelukast is used as add-on therapy in asthma management and can help reduce exercise-induced bronchoconstriction."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/","The Australian Asthma Handbook. Available from: https://www.asthmahandbook.org.au"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51362"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16489"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51362","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51362"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-27T14:54:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-04T11:51:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9180"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65916"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"descr